title: Tour de Dung #1
description: Tour De Dung Road Race #1: March 8th 2014. PRESENTED BY: THE GARAGE AND AUDI CYCLING TEAMS First of two races in the rain shadow of the Olympic Mountain Range.
course: COURSE: Very flat fast good surfaced course (2-3 rollers) but wind frequently has been a factor usually out of the west between 10 to 20 mph. Course is the same as in years past.However this year finish will be at end of Lotzgesell Rd before corner at Cays road. For Map see http://racing.garagebilliards.com/
registration: Each race $30 which includes Washington State Taxes. Registration opens at 8:45 AM and closes 15 minutes prior to the start of your race. Annual USA Cycling Licenses ONLY: One day licenses for Cat 5 Men and Cat 4 Women only. WSBA numbers: Will be used and can be purchased at www.wsbaracing.com (not for sale at the race). Rental numbers: Will be available at the race for a $10 rental fee ($5 is refundable). For out-of-state riders there is no fee to rent a number just a $5 deposit. In order for specific Women Cat 4A & Woman Beginner, i.e. Cat 4B, fields to be offered a Minimum field size of 20 for Women Cat 4A & Women Cat 4B fields must be pre-registered by 3/5. Pre-registered field sizes not met will result in a combination of these two fields to be run at the 10am time and will cancel the mentor/clinics as listed.
notes: Parking and porta-lets will be located in the field across the road from the Dungeness State Park and Recreation Area. RACE NUMBERS: WSBA numbers on the LEFT hand side of jerseys and on frame. On site Coffeesnacks will be avaliable. More race and Prize details will be posted closer to event on http://racing.garagebilliards.com/
directions: LOCATION: Sequim, Dungeness, Washington. From Seattle using the Bainbridge Island Ferry: Exit the ferry at Winslow. Stay on SR 305 to Poulsbo. Proceed through Poulsbo and take SR 3 north (follow signs to the Hood Canal Bridge). Follow directions from Hood Canal Bridge. From the Edmunds-Kingston Ferry: Remain on SR 104 the Canal Bridge. Follow directions from Hood Canal Bridge. From Tacoma: Take SR 16 from the Tacoma Narrows Bridge north. At the junction with SR 3, take SR 3 north to the Hood Canal Bridge. Directions from Hood Canal Bridge: At the Hood Canal Bridge, make a left turn (right turn if you are coming from Kingston) and proceed across the bridge (on SR 104). Follow SR 104 to the junction with US Hwy 101. Take US 101 North toward Pt. Townsend and Pt. Angeles. Follow US 101 past Sequim, stay on Highway 101 until you reach Kitchen Dick Road, take a right onto Kitchen Dick Road. Continue on Kitchen Dick Road, past Woodcock when you will be on the race course, all the way to Lotzgesell Road Rd where the parking area and Start/Finish location. From Olympia and South: Take US Hwy 101 north. Follow US 101 past Sequim, stay on Highway 101 until you reach Kitchen Dick Road, take a right onto Kitchen Dick Road. Continue on Kitchen Dick Road, past Woodcock when you will be on the race course, all the way to Lotzgesell Road Rd where the parking area and Start.

title: Sumner Buckley Kermesse
description: The Sumner Buckley  is a 2014 Northwest Kermesse Series event. The Northwest Kermesse series of events evoke the mythical races described by  juniors cyclists returning from Belgium.   Northwest Kermesse races feature a balance of paved and dirt road and reward riders that display tenacity.
course: Race starts and finishes on Radke Rd and will run clockwise.  The course is flat and approximately 3.9 miles in length with 1.4 miles dirt and 2.5 miles paved road.
registration:
$30 online USACycling.org or $35 day of at Maris Farm.  Registration closes 20 minutes before the start of each event. The entry fee includes $3 per rider per day for USA Cycling insurance. A current year USA Cycling Rider Waiver and Release form must be signed by the participant and, if under 18, by the parent or legal 
guardian.
notes:
While Kermesse races are hard, they are also accessible to new and novice riders.  The dirt section are not technical and unlike regular road races riders that are dropped are able to continue to fight to the finish and it is common to see riders catch groups ahead of them.  Either road or cyclocross bikes can be used but 25 - 28c tires are highly recommended.  Neutral wheel pits will be available on the course. C Race: Cat 4/5s will receive upgrade points based on the road race points schedule.  Full stop.
 
B Races: Cat 3 riders will receive upgrade points based on the road race points schedule for their placing relative to other Cat 3s.   This means if you get 5th in the 1/2/3 race but are the 1st placed Cat 3 you get points for a 1st Place finish.   
 
A Race: Cat 1 / 2 riders will receive upgrade points based on the Criterium points schedule for their overall placing.   This means if you get 5thin the 1/2/3 race but are the 1st placed Cat 2 you get points for a 5thPlace finish.   
 
Scoring:
Masters and Women’s start together but are scored separately.   Masters races will have an overall winner as well as separate scoring for 1-2-3 and 4-5 groups for USACycling Ranking points.  Promoter may separate fields if size warrants.
 
Series Points:
Series points will be for the Cat 1/2/3 Race, Masters Overall (1-5) and Women’s fields.  Series winner will receive a winner’s jersey and free entry into 2015 series events.
directions:
•	Main parking, registration and staging will be at the Take Root Farm in Buckley.  Address is: 22416 Buckley Tapps Hwy E, Buckley, WA 98321.
•	Overflow Parking will be on 246th Ave East, Buckley WA (this is a dead end road opposite Maris Farms).

title: Pipeline Family Gravel Grinder
description: The Pipeline Gravel Grinder is a family friendly cycling event.  The purpose of this event is to give riders an accessible entry into the exciting world of mixed road surface events.  There are three groups (waves) that riders can choose from: a fast group, a moderate group and a family group.  Riders can choose from these three groups depending on their comfort and ability level on mixed paved and gravel roads.  The gravel segments are not technical and can be ridden using road bikes.
course: The course is a 10 mile point-to-point route that starts at the White River School Parking lot off the Foothills trail and then heads out to the unpaved Pipleane Trail to Lake Tapps.  The course is mostly ribinou (dirt road) and 25c tires are advised.  A course map is here http://www.mapmyride.com/routes/view/384648268.  Rules of the road apply, however most of the course is on restricted pipeline access road with limited interactions with cars.  The fast and moderate paced groups will return via Sumner Buckley Highway.  Family participants will return using the course and avoiding the highway.
registration: Register via USACycling or day of.   Day of registration is an extra $5.
notes: Three self-seeded groups will leave at different times..  The first wave is for faster riders and will leave at 9:00am,   A strava segment will be set-up so that riders can compare their times if they choose.   The second wave is intended for riders who want to ride at a slower pace or have not ridden ribinou roads and want to get an easy introduction.  The final wave is a family ride and is intended for kids.   Children under 10 must be accompanied by an adult.  Riders who register in the A or B race may ride the Family wave as well with a child at no cost.
directions:
Start will be at the Visitor Parking for the White River School District next to this address: 305 N River Ave
Buckley, WA 98321

title: SCCA/Starbucks Omnium
description:
One Day, Three Races!
The SCCA/Starbucks Cycling Omnium brought to you by Rairdon's Fiat of Kirland

Race all three or just race one (Omnium Format).

If you race all three you are entered into the individual overall contest. The overall contest is based on the combined time gap of all three events. Your category for the overall is based off the average (rounded, .5 rounded down) cat of your team in the TTT. ie. if a Cat 1 races with 3 - Cat 3's they will all be racing as Cat 2's for the overall as they have a team average of 2.5.
The prices listed are for a single race, when you add a 2nd/3rd race they are just $5 each
course: Located at Pacific Raceways in Kent, WA. See event site for details on courses and duration: http://twd415.wix.com/veloproductions
registration:

Please notify me of your team member for the Team Time Trial and Team Relay by email at veloproductions@outlook.com

title: Tour De Lentil Fun Ride
description: The Tour de Lentil is a 50km, 100km or 150km bike ride (not a race) through the scenic Palouse.  Held in conjunction with the National Lentil Festival, the ride starts and finishes in Pullman, WA.  Proceeds benefit the WSU Cycling Club.
course:
Three course options:
50k course: http://ridewithgps.com/routes/2510777
100k course: http://ridewithgps.com/routes/2510965
150k course: http://ridewithgps.com/routes/2511022
registration:
Registration includes water and snacks at aid stations along the course and a post-race BBQ.  Dry-fit T-shirt guaranteed with early registration. 
Packet Pick-up:  August 22, 3:00pm - 7:00 pm at the Pullman City Play fields
notes:
Riders must be 18 years old minimum to participate 
This event is a ride, not a race.
All riders must wear helmets.
iPods or mp3 players are not permitted.
Use of aero-bars while riding in a group is discouraged.
This course follows city, state and county roads - riders must obey the rules of the road and yield to traffic.
The courses will be marked with on-pavement markings and some signs.  Riders will be provided with directions as well.
All riders will receive a bib number which they are required to wear, and all riders should return to the finish. This helps us make sure you get back safely.
The Tour de Lentil course is very hilly (and often windy) - it is best to prepare for a challenging ride.
150k route riders should have at least a couple 70-80 mile training rides under their belt in the weeks leading up to the event to ensure they are fit enough to complete the event.
Water will be available approximately every 15-17 miles. Please bring multiple water bottles to stay hydrated. Electrolyte supplements and sunscreen are also a good idea.
Note the earlier start times for the 100k and 150k this year per the request of past participants (to reduce heat/sun exposure). Please come to packet pickup the day before to ensure we start on time.
WSU Cycling reserves the right to change the course routes, departure time, and other details for safety or other reasons.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GUgE5mK4SdU
directions:
Pullman City Playfields
(by the softball fields under the bridge)
Spring Street
Pullman, WA

title: Brad Lewis Memorial Cyclocross Race
description:
The BLMCross Race is a cyclocross race produced by the Recycled Cycles Racing team in memory of former team mate Brad Lewis who passed away during a race in 2006.
